title: For Sale:  model 1935 Paruvian Mauser
postcontent:
This Mauser is rare and unusual weapon.  It was made for the military of Peruvian Government on lease for Mauser, by FN, at the facility in Hertsal Belgium.  These rifles were made between 1935 and 1936.  Due to influence of the Peruvian national marksmanship team, the flip wing safety was reversed.  These are the only Mausers ever made in this configuration.  The weapon was on safe when the safety was on the left side ( in front of the shooters eye) and on fire when the safe was on the right side (opposite of the shooters eye). 
    Both the Peruvian seal on the front of the action and the model number on the side, show this  rifle to be a Peruvian model 1935.
   These were the last bolt action rifles purchased by the Peruvians.  They stayed in service until the 1950's when the Government of Peru purchases 30-06 surplus rifles from the US.  Some of the model 1935 Mausers were converted to 30-06's either the factory in Belgium or
By their technicians.  They got new barrels and were rebuilt.  This rife is one of those as can be seen by the ".30" they all had stamped into the Lower receiver.
   Besides it's undetermined value due to its rarity, this is a silky smooth auctioned, accurate and fun gun to shoot.  30-06 ammo is still readily availible and is a great round for hunting everything in North America.  It would be sporterized with little effort for hunting.
   This is a quality Mauser action and would also be perfect for building a custom Mauser rifle in virtually any caliber one could choose.
    This gun is worth every penny being asked right now, and potentially a lot more. Photos are availible upon request.

title: For Sale:  Sig-Sauer P6 9mm German Police Pistol with 2 magazines, similar to P225
postcontent:
Very nice GERMAN made Sig P6 9mm with two magazines for sale. Produced in January, 1981 but still feels solid as new.

This is the German Police version of the P225 and is single-stack with an 8rd capacity making it legal to own in some less gun-friendly areas. Features are the same as other Sig-Sauer pistols and most aftermarket accessories will fit this model including grips, hammers, sights etc.

From what I have seen, these guns *lose* value when modified so I left it as-is, including the holster wear, original grips and the notched hammer. Research has told me this was to indicate if the pistol had been dropped on it's hammer so the armourers could pull it from service but as you can see, this one is intact.

German-made Sig-Sauer pistols are the best in my opinion and they hold value very well. This one is being sold to fund an NFA item and must go soon since the wait is... long.
